When you rely on data which is retrieved using `AJAX`, you should wait to recieve the [promise][1] from [fetch][2]. 

So, let&#39;s say you API function is

    function callAPI(){
        return fetch(&quot;https://api.propublica.org/congress/v1/113/senate/members.json&quot;,{
                method:&quot;GET&quot;,
                headers:{
                         &quot;Content-type&quot;: &quot;application/json&quot;,
                         &quot;X-API-Key&quot;: &quot;eKDuyBWdpQGhsiKGi7geFoBmJR3kCRIRUGRWIASL&quot; 
            }
        });
    }

This function will return the `HTTP` promise.

So, in the caller function you can catch the data.

    function caller(){
      try {
        callAPI().then( (response)=&gt;{
          if(response.ok){
            console.log(response.json());
          }else{
            throw new Error(&#39;BAD HTTP stuff&#39;);
          }
        });
       } catch(err) {
            console.log(&#39;ERROR: &#39;, err.message);
       };  
    }


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Promise
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Fetch_API

```
