The enlightenment came after I upgraded Boost from V1.60 to V1.71 and my problems persisted. I was sure that I had deleted the old files with **`rm -vf`**.&lt;br&gt;
So I looked at this closer.&lt;br&gt;
It sure was not sync(1) because some problems persisted after `sync`ing.
I looked at the GCC tools, which I use (this is Linux). It turned out that it HAS a little known (to me) compiler cache utility, CCACHE(1).&lt;br&gt;
So I cleared the compiler cache, **`ccache -c`**. This made visible that the Boost lib tool does not compile some headers for some sui-generis reason, including regex and xpressive, which I use.&lt;br&gt;
So I corrected that and Voil&#225;! everything worked :-)&lt;br&gt;

